I have a projectile node prefab with a rigid body. Using InstanceXML, they spawn at the world origin and it seems to take them a frame (physics?) before they move to the correct position.

Inside the function that spawns the projectile, after instancing the node its position is correct:

```
void fire_projectile(...)
{
    // Instance the prefab
    XMLFile@ xml = cache.GetResource("XMLFile", "Objects/" + prefab + ".xml");
    // ...
    auto@ node = scene.InstantiateXML(xml, position, rotation);
    Print("node: " + node.worldPosition.ToString());    // correct position
    // ...
}
```

Though when I inspect the node position from a "Projectile" ScriptObject, I noticed that the node is at (0,0,0), while the body is at the correct position:

```
class Projectile : ScriptObject
{
    void DelayedStart()
    {
        Print("start: " + node.worldPosition.ToString());   // 0,0,0
        Print("start body: " + body.position.ToString());   // correct position
    }
}
```

Projectiles can be seen at the world origin. In the case of rocket projectiles, if they spawn straight into collision they will explode at the world origin.
Example video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9om6S8XMYBk

Note that the fire_projectile() print appears before the DelayedStart() print.

vsync seems to make this problem disappear.
